Shared Qs (norm_prob)


  1. Question

    Random variable \(B\) is normally distributed with mean \(\mu = 480\) and standard deviation \(\sigma = 150\). \[B \sim \text{N}(480,\,150) \] Evaluate \(P(B < 390)\).


    Solution

    0.2743

    The easy way (use an online app)

    Go to either:

    • chadworley.github.io/a2/tools/normal.html
      • Set \(\mu\) to 480
      • Set \(\sigma\) to 150
      • Choose Left interval (radio button)
      • Set \(b\) to 390.
    • www.desmos.com/calculator
      • Type NORMALDIST(480,150)
      • Click Find Cumulative Probability (CDF).
      • Enter 390 as Max.

    video (using app)

    The hard way (with a \(z\) table)

    video (using z-table)

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(B\) axis by adding integer multiples of 150 to 480. We know to shade toward the left because small values of \(B\) satisfy the condition \(B<390\).


    We are given a specific \(b\) value as a boundary. (Remember, for random variables we use uppercase letters, but for specific values we use lowercase.) \[b = 390 \] We calculate the \(z\) value of the boundary. \[\begin{aligned} z &= \frac{b-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{390-480}{150} \\\\ &= -0.6 \end{aligned}\]

    We have rephrased our problem into a standard normal probability problem, because \[P(B<390) ~=~ P(Z<-0.6) \]

    So, we just need to evaluate \(P(Z<-0.6)\). To do this, you just need a \(z\)-table.

    \(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
    -0.62 0.2676
    -0.61 0.2709
    -0.6 0.2743
    -0.59 0.2776
    -0.58 0.281

    Thus, we find our answer. \[P(B<390) = 0.2743 \]

  11. Question

    Random variable \(A\) is normally distributed with mean \(\mu = 0.96\) and standard deviation \(\sigma = 0.3\). \[A \sim \text{N}(0.96,\,0.3) \] Evaluate \(P(A > 0.84)\).


    Solution

    0.6554

    Use an online app

    Go to either:

    • chadworley.github.io/a2/tools/normal.html
      • Set \(\mu\) to 0.96
      • Set \(\sigma\) to 0.3
      • Choose Right interval (radio button)
      • Set \(b\) to 0.84.
    • www.desmos.com/calculator
      • Type NORMALDIST(0.96,0.3)
      • Click Find Cumulative Probability (CDF).
      • Enter 0.84 as Min.

    video (using app)

    Using z table

    video (using z-table)

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(A\) axis by adding integer multiples of 0.3 to 0.96. We know to shade toward the right because large values of \(A\) satisfy the condition \(A>0.84\).


    We are given a specific \(a\) value as a boundary. (Remember, for random variables we use uppercase letters, but for specific values we use lowercase.) \[a = 0.84 \] We calculate the \(z\) value of the boundary. \[\begin{aligned} z &= \frac{a-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{0.84-0.96}{0.3} \\\\ &= -0.4 \end{aligned}\]

    We have rephrased our problem into a standard normal probability problem, because \[P(A>0.84) ~=~ P(Z>-0.4) \]

    So, we just need to evaluate \(P(Z>-0.4)\).

    To do this, you need to remember that right-area events are complementary to left-area events. \[P(Z>-0.4) ~=~ 1-P(Z<-0.4) \]

    You can use a \(z\)-table.

    \(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
    -0.42 0.3372
    -0.41 0.3409
    -0.4 0.3446
    -0.39 0.3483
    -0.38 0.352

    Thus, we find our answer. \[\begin{aligned} P(A>0.84) &= 1-0.3446 \\ &= 0.6554 \end{aligned}\]

  21. Question

    Random variable \(C\) is normally distributed with mean \(\mu = 35\) and standard deviation \(\sigma = 5\). \[C \sim \text{N}(35,\,5) \] Evaluate \(P\left(\big|C-35\big| < 7\right)\). In other words, what is the probability that \(C\) is within \(\pm7\) units from the mean?


    Solution

    0.8384

    Use online app

    Go to either:

    • chadworley.github.io/a2/tools/normal.html
      • Set \(\mu\) to 35
      • Set \(\sigma\) to 5
      • Choose center interval (radio button)
      • Set \(r\) to 7.
    • www.desmos.com/calculator
      • Type NORMALDIST(35,5)
      • Click Find Cumulative Probability (CDF).
      • Enter 35 as Min. Notice, \(42-7=35\).
      • Enter 49 as Max. Notice, \(42+7=49\).

    video (using app)

    Use z table

    video (using z-table)

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(C\) axis by adding integer multiples of 5 to 35. We know to shade the center because values near 35 satisfy the condition \(\big|C-35\big| < 7\). We draw the boundaries at \(35-7=28\) and \(35+7=42\) because those are the solutions to \(\big|C-35\big| = 7\). We can also rephrase the probability.

    \[P\left(\big|C-35\big| < 7\right) ~=~ P(28<C<42)\]


    We calculate the \(z\) values of the boundaries. Left boundary: \[\begin{aligned} z_1 &= \frac{28-35}{5} \\\\ &= \frac{-7}{5} \\\\ &= -1.4 \end{aligned}\]

    Right boundary:

    \[\begin{aligned} z_2 &= \frac{42-35}{5} \\\\ &= \frac{7}{5} \\\\ &= 1.4 \end{aligned}\]

    We have rephrased our problem into a standard normal probability problem, because

    \[P\left(\big|C-35\big| < 7\right) ~=~ P(28<C<42) ~=~ P(-1.4<Z<1.4) ~=~ P\left(\big|Z\big|<1.4\right)\]

    So, we just need to evaluate \(P(|Z|<1.4)\). I will also point out that \(\frac{7}{5} = 1.4\). In general, if \(X\) is normally distributed, then: \[P\left(\big|X-\mu\big|<d\right) ~=~ P\left(\big|Z\big| < \frac{d}{\sigma}\right)\]

    From here we have a formula that lets us use the \(z\) table. \[\begin{aligned} P(|Z|<1.4) &= 2 \times P(Z<1.4)-1 \\ &= 2 \times 0.9192-1 \\ &= 0.8384 \end{aligned}\]

    video (using z-table)

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(W\) axis by adding integer multiples of 40 to 340. We know to shade the two tails because values far from 340 satisfy the condition \(\big|W-340\big| > 60\). We draw the boundaries at \(340-60=280\) and \(340+60=400\) because those are the solutions to \(\big|W-340\big| = 60\). We can also rephrase the probability.

    \[P\left(\big|W-340\big| > 60\right) ~=~ P\big(W<280 \text{ OR } W>400\big)\]


    We calculate the \(z\) values of the boundaries. Left boundary: \[\begin{aligned} z_1 &= \frac{280-340}{40} \\\\ &= \frac{-60}{40} \\\\ &= -1.5 \end{aligned}\]

    Right boundary:

    \[\begin{aligned} z_2 &= \frac{400-340}{40} \\\\ &= \frac{60}{40} \\\\ &= 1.5 \end{aligned}\]

    We have rephrased our problem into a standard normal probability problem, because

    \[P\left(\big|W-340\big| > 60\right) ~=~ P\left(\big|Z\big|>1.5\right)\]

    So, we just need to evaluate \(P(|Z|>1.5)\). I will also point out that \(\frac{60}{40} = 1.5\). In general, if \(X\) is normally distributed, then: \[P\left(\big|X-\mu\big|>d\right) ~=~ P\left(\big|Z\big| > \frac{d}{\sigma}\right)\]

    From here we have a formula that lets us use the \(z\) table. (We practiced this part before.) \[\begin{aligned} P(|Z|>1.5) &= 2- 2 \times P(Z<1.5) \\ &= 2 - 2 \times 0.9332 \\ &= 0.1336 \end{aligned}\]

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(D\) axis by adding integer multiples of 6 to 25. We know to shade the between \(25\) and \(28\) because those values satisfy the condition \(25 < D < 28\).


    We calculate the \(z\) values of the boundaries. Left boundary: \[\begin{aligned} z_1 &= \frac{d_1-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{25-25}{6} \\\\ &= 0 \end{aligned}\]

    Right boundary:

    \[\begin{aligned} z_2 &= \frac{d_2-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{28-25}{6} \\\\ &= 0.5 \end{aligned}\]

    We rephrase our problem into a standard normal probability problem:

    \[P\left(25 < D < 28\right) ~=~ P(0<Z<0.5)\]

    So, we just need to evaluate \(P(0<Z<0.5)\).

    From here we have a formula that lets us use the \(z\) table. (We practiced this part before.) \[\begin{aligned} P(z_1 < Z < z_2) &= P(Z<z_2) - P(Z<z1) \\ P(0<Z<0.5) &= P(Z<0.5)-P(Z<0)\\ &= 0.6915-0.5 \\ &= 0.1915 \end{aligned}\]



  50. Question

    Random variable \(Y\) is normally distributed with mean \(\mu = 0.22\) and standard deviation \(\sigma = 0.03\). \[Y \sim \text{N}(0.22,\,0.03) \] Evaluate \(P\left(0.19 < Y < 0.25\right)\). In other words, what is the probability that \(Y\) is between \(0.19\) and \(0.25\)?


    Solution

    Online app

    • chadworley.github.io/a2/tools/normal.html
      • Set \(\mu\) to 0.22
      • Set \(\sigma\) to 0.03
      • Choose between interval (radio button)
      • Set \(b_1\) to 0.19.
      • Set \(b_2\) to 0.25.
    • www.desmos.com/calculator
      • Type NORMALDIST(0.22,0.03)
      • Click Find Cumulative Probability (CDF).
      • Enter 0.19 as Min.
      • Enter 0.25 as Max.

    Z table

    video (using z-table)

    First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(Y\) axis by adding integer multiples of 0.03 to 0.22. We know to shade the between \(0.19\) and \(0.25\) because those values satisfy the condition \(0.19 < Y < 0.25\).


    We calculate the \(z\) values of the boundaries. Left boundary: \[\begin{aligned} z_1 &= \frac{y_1-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{0.19-0.22}{0.03} \\\\ &= -1 \end{aligned}\]

    Right boundary:

    \[\begin{aligned} z_2 &= \frac{y_2-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{0.25-0.22}{0.03} \\\\ &= 1 \end{aligned}\]

    We rephrase our problem into a standard normal probability problem:

    \[P\left(0.19 < Y < 0.25\right) ~=~ P(-1<Z<1)\]

    So, we just need to evaluate \(P(-1<Z<1)\).

    From here we have a formula that lets us use the \(z\) table. (We practiced this part before.) \[\begin{aligned} P(z_1 < Z < z_2) &= P(Z<z_2) - P(Z<z1) \\ P(-1<Z<1) &= P(Z<1)-P(Z<-1)\\ &= 0.8413-0.1587 \\ &= 0.6826 \end{aligned}\]
